{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530579"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:08:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:08:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14554"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14554"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.08,0.02,0.47,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58469"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7247"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14554"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43885"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1914"},{"type":"tags","id":"3475"},{"type":"tags","id":"4067"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18243"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58469"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man with known alcoholic liver cirrhosis has been admitted to the general medical ward with worsening ascites. Several hours after his admission the duty intern is called by the nurse to review the patient because the patient is now complaining of severe generalised abdominal pain and has vomited twice in the last hour. He has a history of heavy alcohol use, drinking 8-10 standard drinks daily for the past 20 years. He takes spironolactone and furosemide for ascites management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His vital signs are: pulse rate 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended with ascites and is diffusely tender with guarding. Bowel sounds are absent.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous ceftriaxone","Abdominal X-ray","Intravenous ondansetron","Diagnostic paracentesis","CT abdomen"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms suggestive of spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP), a serious and potentially life-threatening complication in patients with cirrhosis and ascites. The most appropriate next step in management is to perform a\u003Cstrong\u003E diagnostic paracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E. This procedure is crucial for confirming the diagnosis of SBP and guiding further management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESBP is characterised by infection of the ascitic fluid without an apparent intra-abdominal source. The patient\u0027s history of alcoholic cirrhosis, severe abdominal pain, vomiting, fever, and signs of peritonitis (abdominal tenderness with guarding) are all consistent with this diagnosis. Diagnostic paracentesis allows for immediate analysis of the ascitic fluid, including cell count, culture, and biochemistry. A neutrophil count \u0026gt;250 cells/mm\u00b3 in the ascitic fluid is diagnostic of SBP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E CT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if there was suspicion of other intra-abdominal pathology, but in this case, the clinical picture is strongly suggestive of SBP and paracentesis should not be delayed for imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdministering \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous ondansetron\u003C/strong\u003E would only address the symptom of vomiting without diagnosing or treating the underlying condition. While antiemetics may be used supportively, they should not delay the diagnostic process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdministering\u003Cstrong\u003E intravenous ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E would be an appropriate step after confirming the diagnosis of SBP. However, it is crucial to obtain ascitic fluid samples for culture before starting antibiotics to ensure proper identification of the causative organism and its antibiotic sensitivities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA plain \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal X-ray \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be more appropriate if bowel obstruction or perforation were the primary concerns. While these conditions can cause severe abdominal pain and vomiting, the patient\u0027s history and examination findings are more suggestive of SBP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter performing the diagnostic paracentesis, if SBP is confirmed, the next steps would include starting empiric antibiotic therapy (typically a third-generation cephalosporin), administering intravenous albumin to reduce the risk of hepatorenal syndrome, and closely monitoring the patient\u0027s clinical status. The patient\u0027s alcohol use history is relevant as it increases the risk of both SBP and acute pancreatitis, highlighting the importance of considering these diagnoses in patients with a history of alcohol misuse presenting with acute abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis is a serious complication in patients with cirrhosis and ascites, requiring prompt diagnosis and treatment."],"references":["Dever JB, Sheikh MY. Review article: spontaneous bacterial peritonitis \u2013 bacteriology, diagnosis, treatment, risk factors and prevention. Aliment Pharmacol Ther 2015; 41: 1116\u201331."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43885"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14554"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43885"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-31T20:19:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T20:19:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7247"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58469"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":